{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17654303","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17654303"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:52:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:52:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18615"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18615","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18615"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11347"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76438"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11347","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11347"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18615"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61935"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10276"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26334"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26341"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76438","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76438"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EType I muscle fibres are specialised for specific physiological functions. They have distinct structural and metabolic characteristics that differentiate them from other muscle fibre types.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes a characteristic of Type I muscle fibres?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["High oxidative capacity with numerous mitochondria","Primarily anaerobic metabolism","Quick onset of fatigue","Low myoglobin content","Rapid contraction speed"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh oxidative capacity with numerous mitochondria\u003C/strong\u003E is a key characteristic of Type I muscle fibres. These fibres contain abundant mitochondria which support their reliance on aerobic metabolism for ATP production. This allows for sustained contractions over long periods.\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERapid contraction speed\u003C/strong\u003E - Type I fibres contract slowly compared to Type II fibres\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELow myoglobin content\u003C/strong\u003E - Type I fibres have high myoglobin content, giving them their red appearance\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrimarily anaerobic metabolism\u003C/strong\u003E - Type I fibres rely predominantly on aerobic metabolism\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EQuick onset of fatigue\u003C/strong\u003E - Type I fibres are highly fatigue-resistant due to their oxidative capacity\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EType I fibres are particularly abundant in postural muscles that require sustained contractions, such as the soleus muscle in the calf. Their high oxidative capacity and fatigue resistance make them well-suited for maintaining posture and performing endurance activities.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Type I (slow oxidative) muscle fibres contain many mitochondria and use aerobic metabolism for sustained contractions.","Type I fibres have high myoglobin content giving them a red appearance and excellent oxygen storage capacity.","Type I fibres are resistant to fatigue and are predominantly found in postural muscles."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relati